1
00:00:02,140 --> 00:00:15,896
Foundation Course 1, Talk 8 The Fourth Noble Truth, Positive Morality, Parami The Buddha taught that morality was the basis of spiritual attainment.

2
00:00:17,097 --> 00:00:21,501
By morality, he didn't mean a set of commandments imposed by a wrathful deity.

3
00:00:22,483 --> 00:00:30,071
He meant simply those rules whereby a harmonious society would be established and a peaceful and loving mind could be developed.

4
00:00:31,839 --> 00:00:38,728
Since all human beings are interdependent, an individual's progress through life is greatly affected by those around and about.

5
00:00:40,029 --> 00:00:51,362
Buddhism often talks about the Kalyanamita, the good friend, and the Buddha himself is often seen as such, a friend, a companion, a true guide who has our best interests at heart.

6
00:00:53,744 --> 00:00:56,868
The primary precepts are the basic guidelines.

7
00:00:56,966 --> 00:01:04,134
They begin with a negative morality, to cease from harm, then comes to do good, a positive morality, the development of virtue.

8
00:01:05,475 --> 00:01:09,439
This was codified in the Theravada tradition as the ten perfections.

9
00:01:10,960 --> 00:01:13,644
Actually, the translation gives the wrong idea as to their aim.

10
00:01:14,665 --> 00:01:21,371
The word for them in Pali is parami, which means the other shore, an image often used for Nibbana.

11
00:01:21,840 --> 00:01:26,846
So really, these ten virtues, when practiced, help us to find our way to liberation.

12
00:01:27,608 --> 00:01:33,316
There's no idea of perfection in terms of coming to some sort of end in their development.

13
00:01:33,335 --> 00:01:37,180
They can be practiced and developed as long as we are alive, to any degree.

14
00:01:39,603 --> 00:01:49,856
The ten perfections are generosity, morality, renunciation, wisdom, effort, patience,

15
00:01:50,140 --> 00:01:55,144
truthfulness, resolution, unconditioned love, and equanimity.

16
00:01:56,986 --> 00:02:02,331
Here we can only give pointers, and I'm sure none of the virtues comes to you as any surprise.

17
00:02:05,516 --> 00:02:08,057
First, then, is dana, generosity.

18
00:02:09,240 --> 00:02:11,882
Dana is a word you will often hear in Buddhist circles.

19
00:02:13,122 --> 00:02:17,548
If the lay people offer food to monks and nuns, for instance, it's called dana.

20
00:02:18,034 --> 00:02:23,864
Dana means, really, to share one's wealth and one's time with others with no thought of return.

21
00:02:25,227 --> 00:02:27,370
Our word donation comes from the same root.

22
00:02:28,893 --> 00:02:39,871
This is very important because it teaches us to let go of our attachment to wealth and frees us from thinking that our lives are to be simply lived for our own personal benefit.

23
00:02:41,673 --> 00:02:43,856
It stops us becoming greedy and miserly.

24
00:02:44,984 --> 00:02:50,652
Walking around the city centre on a flag day for a charity, do we ignore the change-jangling boxes?

25
00:02:51,433 --> 00:02:54,177
Do we instinctively reach into our purse?

26
00:02:55,439 --> 00:02:59,066
If we do, and find only a pound coin, do we still put it in?

27
00:02:59,847 --> 00:03:04,253
Or do we listen to the barrage of voices in our minds crying, too much, too much?

28
00:03:07,138 --> 00:03:12,425
Generosity with time softens our unwillingness to spend time for the benefit of others.

29
00:03:13,132 --> 00:03:17,716
Those precious moments of our lives we would normally devote entirely to our own pleasures and interests.

30
00:03:19,137 --> 00:03:21,639
How do we feel when children ask for help with homework?

31
00:03:22,240 --> 00:03:23,461
Or a parent asks for help?

32
00:03:23,980 --> 00:03:25,962
Or a friend makes a social call?

33
00:03:26,804 --> 00:03:28,985
Do we say, we're too busy, too tired?

34
00:03:30,706 --> 00:03:37,552
Generosity with our wealth and time helps us to put our life, our life's work, our relationships into a greater perspective.

35
00:03:38,574 --> 00:03:42,176
The question arises, why should I give my money to another?

36
00:03:42,949 --> 00:03:45,933
Why should I spend any time of my life helping another?

37
00:03:47,376 --> 00:03:50,900
It is only in so doing and reaping the benefits that we can discover the answer.

38
00:03:53,503 --> 00:04:01,875
The second is morality, which means to guard against any unskillful actions and to produce eventually a mind free of greed, hatred and delusion.

39
00:04:02,616 --> 00:04:05,098
This is one description of a Buddhist saint, the Arahant.

40
00:04:05,780 --> 00:04:07,823
Arahant literally means to kill one's enemies.

41
00:04:08,043 --> 00:04:08,543
What enemies?

42
00:04:09,003 --> 00:04:09,705
The enemies within.

43
00:04:10,186 --> 00:04:12,027
Greed, hatred and delusions.

44
00:04:13,712 --> 00:04:14,933
The third is renunciation.

45
00:04:15,974 --> 00:04:20,120
Although this can often have a feel of sacrifice about it, that is not the kernel of it.

46
00:04:21,040 --> 00:04:24,064
It's being able to give something up once you know it's no good for you.

47
00:04:25,545 --> 00:04:33,495
We like to drink, but when we come to know that alcohol does to the body and mind, we may decide to cut back or stop altogether.

48
00:04:34,194 --> 00:04:40,362
Either way, renouncing drink means we have to go through the barrier of obsessive desires, the very habits of drinking.

49
00:04:41,319 --> 00:04:45,526
Often renunciation comes about because of weariness with some old habit.

50
00:04:46,728 --> 00:04:53,180
Perhaps a person stops drinking because she suddenly realizes it's just an empty social habit devoid of any intrinsic meaning.

51
00:04:54,482 --> 00:04:59,168
Renunciation includes having the strength of character to give up what is harmful to us.

52
00:05:02,074 --> 00:05:07,463
Wisdom, the fourth perfection, means to undermine our delusions and illusions about ourselves.

53
00:05:08,826 --> 00:05:15,396
By the practice of awareness, both in meditation and during our daily lives, we can begin to see ourselves more objectively.

54
00:05:17,059 --> 00:05:22,185
As we do this, ignorance about ourselves is dispelled and wisdom, real self-knowledge, grows.

55
00:05:23,827 --> 00:05:27,793
The fifth parami, effort, is raising the will to do, to act.

56
00:05:28,836 --> 00:05:31,899
It's raising the energy needed to accomplish the task.

57
00:05:31,920 --> 00:05:35,685
In the spiritual field, that means the primary precepts.

58
00:05:35,704 --> 00:05:38,209
We must make effort to cease from doing harm.

59
00:05:38,829 --> 00:05:43,536
We must put forth effort to do good, good for ourselves and others.

60
00:05:44,577 --> 00:05:47,081
We have to raise the effort to purify the mind.

61
00:05:47,942 --> 00:05:56,115
This constant effort to raise energy undermines our unwholesome tendency towards sleepiness, laziness, not bothering, leaving it to others, apathy.

62
00:05:57,737 --> 00:06:02,745
It won't allow boredom and depression to trick us into escape routes and hopelessness.

63
00:06:04,884 --> 00:06:10,091
The sixth, patience, the Buddha said was the highest ascetism.

64
00:06:10,110 --> 00:06:16,858
The word kanti in Pali is variously translated as patience, forbearance or forgiveness.

65
00:06:18,120 --> 00:06:20,283
Our own word patience is interesting also.

66
00:06:21,144 --> 00:06:22,886
Its Latin root means suffering.

67
00:06:24,286 --> 00:06:26,449
Patience is the willingness to accept suffering.

68
00:06:27,490 --> 00:06:31,095
In our meditation, this is a virtue of great importance.

69
00:06:31,834 --> 00:06:40,624
When we sit, all our negative states of mind begin to surface, our great angers, grudges, depressions, anxieties, fears, doubts, and so on.

70
00:06:41,764 --> 00:06:45,488
All nasty feelings in the body, some very uncomfortable indeed.

71
00:06:46,589 --> 00:06:51,134
What is more, the pain of the sitting posture, especially at the knees, can become quite sharp.

72
00:06:52,536 --> 00:06:57,740
Being able to sit still in the midst of this suffering is a prerequisite for insight wisdom.

73
00:06:57,939 --> 00:07:08,458
That attitude which says, yes, there's a lot of pain in me, I feel it, but I'm just going to sit here patiently, equanimously, and put all my effort into watching it keenly.

74
00:07:09,660 --> 00:07:14,228
This sort of attitude is absolutely paramount to the whole process of mental purification.

75
00:07:14,983 --> 00:07:24,334
Up until now, we've run away from pain, from pain to pain, either dousing it out with pills or finding some other way of distracting the mind.

76
00:07:25,076 --> 00:07:26,257
Anything but face up to it.

77
00:07:26,978 --> 00:07:32,004
But as the Buddha has pointed out so clearly in the First Noble Truth, this is but a foolish escapism.

78
00:07:33,384 --> 00:07:36,468
By facing pain and suffering, we lose our fear of it.

79
00:07:36,668 --> 00:07:49,043
When we see pain and suffering for what it really is, then we can say we have achieved an important insight into the human state, and it is this understanding that leads us towards our final emancipation from all suffering.

80
00:07:51,466 --> 00:07:54,411
The Jataka tales comprise many volumes.

81
00:07:55,372 --> 00:08:00,499
They are stories made up after the death of the Buddha, purportedly telling of his past lives.

82
00:08:02,302 --> 00:08:07,427
Before his enlightenment, the Buddha is called the Bodhisatta, one who is seeking enlightenment.

83
00:08:08,687 --> 00:08:13,132
In this interesting little story, he is said to have been born an ascetic called Kundaka.

84
00:08:14,254 --> 00:08:16,355
It shows us how far patience can be taken.

85
00:08:17,576 --> 00:08:23,002
It would seem that the king Kalaka had gone with his dancing girls for a lavish picnic in a pleasure grove.

86
00:08:23,803 --> 00:08:27,206
He fell asleep and the girls wandered off to delight in the grove.

87
00:08:27,827 --> 00:08:29,528
They came across the ascetic Kundaka.

88
00:08:30,230 --> 00:08:32,292
They fell in conversation with him about the Dharma.

89
00:08:33,182 --> 00:08:37,005
When the king woke up and found out what had happened, he was furious with jealousy.

90
00:08:38,027 --> 00:08:43,591
But for the intervention of one of his favorite ladies, he would have cut the Bodhisattva down there and then.

91
00:08:43,631 --> 00:08:47,835
Instead, maliciously, he asked the ascetic what he taught.

92
00:08:48,515 --> 00:08:55,241
The ascetic answered, It is to have no anger when another abuses, strikes, or humiliates you.

93
00:08:56,863 --> 00:09:02,548
The cruel king Kalaka decided to put him to the test and had his executioner lash him two thousand times.

94
00:09:03,337 --> 00:09:12,812
When asked for his response, the ascetic kundaka, the Bodhisatta, replies, I teach patience, sire, but you think my patience is only skin deep.

95
00:09:13,231 --> 00:09:13,712
It is not.

96
00:09:14,354 --> 00:09:17,258
My patience is rooted deeply in my heart.

97
00:09:18,580 --> 00:09:21,024
The king then had his hands chopped off, then his feet.

98
00:09:22,044 --> 00:09:29,756
Again the ascetic declared, You think, sire, my patience is in my hands and my feet, but it is deep within my being.

99
00:09:30,738 --> 00:09:32,080
Off came his ears and nose.

100
00:09:32,735 --> 00:09:36,058
but the ascetic Bodhisattva declared his patience was deep in the heart.

101
00:09:36,980 --> 00:09:42,888
Annoyed by his defeat, the king kicks him and departs, only to be swallowed up into the deepest of hells, the Ricci.

102
00:09:43,769 --> 00:09:48,115
That same day, the Bodhisattva also dies, but not without this verse of forgiveness.

103
00:09:49,456 --> 00:09:55,024
The king, who had my hands, feet, ears, and nose cut off, let him live long.

104
00:09:55,745 --> 00:09:59,129
Those who are as I am cannot be angry.

105
00:10:00,476 --> 00:10:04,042
So you see there's no limit to how much we can develop the perfections.

106
00:10:06,625 --> 00:10:07,687
Truthfulness is the seventh.

107
00:10:08,467 --> 00:10:12,953
To strive for that absolute honesty, not only with others, but with ourselves too.

108
00:10:13,654 --> 00:10:19,663
It may take courage sometimes to face others and ourselves, but truthfulness means the inability to deceive.

109
00:10:20,705 --> 00:10:27,514
It means to search for the authentic, to do what is right and proper in our relationships, in our society and towards ourselves.

110
00:10:27,982 --> 00:10:31,647
It asks us to see things as they really are, warts and all.

111
00:10:32,707 --> 00:10:35,971
In its perfection, it's to seek the ultimate truth, nibbana.

112
00:10:38,033 --> 00:10:39,056
The eighth is resolution.

113
00:10:39,816 --> 00:10:42,198
The path to hell is paved with good intentions.

114
00:10:42,559 --> 00:10:42,940
How true.

115
00:10:44,261 --> 00:10:47,524
If only we'd done this, done that, we'd be so happy now.

116
00:10:48,966 --> 00:10:50,128
Resolution is stickability.

117
00:10:50,148 --> 00:10:50,869
Stickability.

118
00:10:51,456 --> 00:10:57,822
the stamina to keep going, going on regardless how hard it is, regardless of the temptations to leave off.

119
00:10:58,303 --> 00:10:59,684
It's to go on going on.

120
00:11:01,267 --> 00:11:09,355
The Buddha himself exercised this perfection when he made his historic decision not to rise from the sitting posture until he had attained enlightenment.

121
00:11:10,676 --> 00:11:11,437
What a resolution!

122
00:11:12,597 --> 00:11:15,120
It took six hours before his breakthrough came.

123
00:11:15,921 --> 00:11:16,400
We can do it.

124
00:11:16,861 --> 00:11:17,182
We can.

125
00:11:17,903 --> 00:11:21,125
We can take up the posture and refuse with all our will

126
00:11:21,679 --> 00:11:24,722
to rise not until we're enlightened.

127
00:11:26,024 --> 00:11:27,866
It would be a real test of our resolution, wouldn't it?

128
00:11:29,307 --> 00:11:32,051
This is one of the reasons it's so difficult to become enlightened.

129
00:11:32,831 --> 00:11:35,394
Our perfection of resolution is not developed enough.

130
00:11:37,176 --> 00:11:40,720
Perhaps a little more realistically, it means to see our decisions through.

131
00:11:41,280 --> 00:11:43,503
If I decide to do something, I should do it.

132
00:11:44,183 --> 00:11:47,366
I should complete the task and complete it to the best of my ability.

133
00:11:48,528 --> 00:11:56,479
If I say I'll help someone with their garden, I should do it, and I should get there early, even if everything in me wants to go shopping instead.

134
00:11:57,620 --> 00:12:02,667
If I say I'm going to sit for half an hour, I should do so to the last minute and add a couple for good measure.

135
00:12:03,908 --> 00:12:07,613
This sort of self-training helps to develop a strong, unwavering mind.

136
00:12:08,634 --> 00:12:12,119
This is not to be confused with a headstrong will-do-or-die business.

137
00:12:12,820 --> 00:12:16,424
It's a matter of honouring our commitments to others and to ourselves.

138
00:12:17,283 --> 00:12:19,947
It leads to self-reliance and to the trust of others.

139
00:12:21,188 --> 00:12:26,336
People know you do as you say, and you know you can do as you say you will do.

140
00:12:27,698 --> 00:12:38,514
Ultimately, it's all training us for that time when we will make our own personal historic decision not to rise, not to be dissuaded from the path, until our total liberation is won.

141
00:12:41,139 --> 00:12:42,159
The ninth is Metta.

142
00:12:42,865 --> 00:12:44,548
A difficult word this to translate.

143
00:12:45,349 --> 00:12:48,234
Loving-kindness is the usual, but some say it's too sloppy.

144
00:12:49,777 --> 00:12:51,620
It's an open-heartedness, friendliness.

145
00:12:52,381 --> 00:12:55,807
It's a universal, unprejudiced, unbiased, impartial love.

146
00:12:56,568 --> 00:12:58,572
Love as care, benevolence, empathy.

147
00:12:59,573 --> 00:13:00,755
There are no favourites.

148
00:13:01,731 --> 00:13:05,277
Even if someone dislikes us, we still develop this attitude towards them.

149
00:13:05,856 --> 00:13:10,643
If I dislike someone, and I want to practice metta, I first of all don't indulge that dislike.

150
00:13:11,224 --> 00:13:19,835
I develop first an attitude of no harm, and as the nasty feelings pass, I can begin to develop more kindly attitudes, looking at that person's better side.

151
00:13:21,616 --> 00:13:23,158
Of course, this is all very difficult.

152
00:13:23,820 --> 00:13:27,705
We are bound to have a greater affinity, greater feelings for those who are close to us.

153
00:13:28,023 --> 00:13:32,328
those whom we meet every day rather than people we hardly know, let alone those we never see.

154
00:13:33,610 --> 00:13:40,922
But it's an ideal we aim to move towards, an unbounded love where all beings are seen through the eye of love and compassion.

155
00:13:42,063 --> 00:13:45,850
It's a generalized attitude, a disposition of care and well-wishing.

156
00:13:47,231 --> 00:13:52,860
Someone I know held a correspondence with a prisoner, who later in a letter confided he had committed rape.

157
00:13:53,861 --> 00:13:56,004
My friend was filled with anger and disgust.

158
00:13:56,845 --> 00:14:09,900
In a letter later, the prisoner explained how through this terrible mistake he had lost all his family, no one wanted to know him, how he had lost his career, and all that on top of being locked away in prison.

159
00:14:11,682 --> 00:14:16,948
When my friend now saw it from the prisoner's angle, he was able to re-establish a sense of sympathy for the man.

160
00:14:17,710 --> 00:14:18,291
This is meta.

161
00:14:20,693 --> 00:14:24,337
There is another side of meta which people find difficult to accept.

162
00:14:24,571 --> 00:14:31,240
And this is to realize that we cannot achieve the goal of universal love if we can't also include ourselves in there.

163
00:14:32,602 --> 00:14:39,373
That is why when we practice Metta Bhavana, loving-kindness meditation, we develop these attitudes towards ourselves.

164
00:14:40,294 --> 00:14:41,716
May I be free of suffering.

165
00:14:42,197 --> 00:14:43,178
May I be peaceful.

166
00:14:43,318 --> 00:14:44,480
May I be liberated.

167
00:14:46,464 --> 00:14:51,692
Some think this is selfishness, but there's a vast difference between eating to live and living to eat.

168
00:14:52,751 --> 00:14:55,615
The one is caring for oneself, looking after oneself.

169
00:14:55,996 --> 00:14:57,219
The other is self-indulgence.

170
00:14:58,740 --> 00:15:01,706
We tend to have a lot of dislike for ourselves.

171
00:15:02,486 --> 00:15:06,854
We are often full of self-recrimination, self-accusations, all those little voices.

172
00:15:07,134 --> 00:15:12,022
I'm no good, I'm useless, I'm ugly, I'm disgusting, I don't know how anybody could possibly like me.

173
00:15:12,201 --> 00:15:14,184
I'm not good enough, no one loves me.

174
00:15:15,447 --> 00:15:15,908
And so on.

175
00:15:17,153 --> 00:15:22,380
We need to undermine these negative feelings towards ourselves by, first of all, not indulging them.

176
00:15:23,342 --> 00:15:24,745
Just listen to them and smile.

177
00:15:25,024 --> 00:15:25,846
No one's perfect.

178
00:15:27,048 --> 00:15:29,633
Then we should develop self-acceptance, self-care.

179
00:15:30,855 --> 00:15:35,923
What would you think of someone who never washed their own clothes and went around like a ragamuffin?

180
00:15:36,624 --> 00:15:38,826
We'd say, that woman doesn't care for herself.

181
00:15:39,368 --> 00:15:41,270
That man has no self-respect.

182
00:15:42,500 --> 00:15:48,807
What would you think of someone who never washed their own clothes, went around like a ragamuffin, but wanted to wash everybody else's clothes?

183
00:15:50,129 --> 00:15:51,070
That's what we're like, isn't it?

184
00:15:51,629 --> 00:15:55,674
We like to take care of everyone else's problems while we haven't a clue what to do with our own.

185
00:15:56,816 --> 00:15:59,960
Sometimes we're so self-deluded we don't think we have any problems.

186
00:16:01,642 --> 00:16:06,847
Being able to take care of ourselves is a qualification for being able to take care of others.

187
00:16:09,309 --> 00:16:11,712
Finally, equanimity, the tenth perfection.

188
00:16:12,672 --> 00:16:16,697
Equanimity is considered to be the highest state of mind in Buddhism.

189
00:16:16,717 --> 00:16:20,323
It is not to be confused with cold detachment or intellectual indifference.

190
00:16:21,225 --> 00:16:25,250
It is a mental state undisturbed by any negative emotions or feelings.

191
00:16:26,393 --> 00:16:28,115
There is no sentimentality here.

192
00:16:29,518 --> 00:16:36,148
It is a state of mind, clear, calm and cool like a still pool in which all the sky is clearly mirrored.

193
00:16:38,052 --> 00:16:50,167
It is within this equanimous mind that the intuition, the faculty of insight, can exercise its power to see, to understand and eventually to liberate the mind of all its illusions and delusions.

194
00:16:51,908 --> 00:16:55,072
It is when our hearts are calm and peaceful that wisdom shines.

195
00:16:56,495 --> 00:17:00,820
The practice of meditation is especially important in developing this sort of mind.

196
00:17:01,794 --> 00:17:10,307
No matter what comes into our attention, we constantly take the position of the objective observer, just watching, just noting what is arising and passing away.

197
00:17:11,631 --> 00:17:14,414
Eventually all this commotion in the mind begins to die down.

198
00:17:15,436 --> 00:17:19,363
You can sometimes feel this relaxation, even after a few minutes sitting.

199
00:17:20,805 --> 00:17:29,018
As the mind's agitation calms, you may experience little gaps of empty mind, where there seems to be no emotion or mood or thought or image.

200
00:17:29,807 --> 00:17:33,451
just pure awareness, being aware of this stillness, this silence.

201
00:17:34,811 --> 00:17:38,015
This is the mind as a calm pool, and awareness is the sky.

202
00:17:39,155 --> 00:17:49,345
When sensations, feelings or mental states arise out of the depth of this pool, the awareness can perceive quite clearly the arising and passing away of all this mental phenomena.

203
00:17:50,546 --> 00:17:58,633
It is with this sort of concentration that there is a possibility of glimpsing what is beyond this phenomena, the nirvanic peace beyond.

204
00:18:00,857 --> 00:18:09,185
Now, in daily life, it's not necessary for us to get all neurotic and keep a tally on what perfection we're practicing and how well we're doing.

205
00:18:10,567 --> 00:18:17,834
The easiest and simplest approach to the development of virtue is to take one of the list which we feel we would like most to develop.

206
00:18:19,095 --> 00:18:21,958
We will find that in its practice all the others are included.

207
00:18:23,578 --> 00:18:29,565
If I decide to practice dana generosity, for instance, well, of course, that means I'm undermining greed.

208
00:18:29,730 --> 00:18:33,494
and I shall hardly be developing the habit of taking what is not freely given to me.

209
00:18:33,994 --> 00:18:34,776
That's morality.

210
00:18:36,397 --> 00:18:39,961
As soon as I give, I also have to renounce a little of my wealth and time.

211
00:18:40,582 --> 00:18:41,221
Renunciation.

212
00:18:42,483 --> 00:18:45,346
As I practice generosity, I come to know its importance.

213
00:18:45,426 --> 00:18:47,689
I come to see how interdependent people are.

214
00:18:48,189 --> 00:18:50,652
Such insights are all developing my wisdom.

215
00:18:52,534 --> 00:18:54,996
To practice any virtue takes effort.

216
00:18:55,938 --> 00:19:00,085
And I need to suffer willingly my discomfort at the loss of wealth and time.

217
00:19:00,625 --> 00:19:01,346
That's patience.

218
00:19:01,988 --> 00:19:03,730
I've learnt how to give gladly.

219
00:19:05,493 --> 00:19:07,857
In all this, I need to be honest with myself.

220
00:19:08,618 --> 00:19:11,884
I must be aware of my reasons, both overt and covert.

221
00:19:12,625 --> 00:19:17,894
Sometimes I think I'm giving with a pure heart, but in fact I'm very upset if the person doesn't thank me.

222
00:19:19,017 --> 00:19:22,182
Honesty might mean becoming aware of our impure motives.

223
00:19:23,646 --> 00:19:26,891
I develop resolution too, in that I carry out my decisions.

224
00:19:28,993 --> 00:19:30,996
In giving, my heart is opened.

225
00:19:31,957 --> 00:19:34,519
I'm giving because I see the other needs my assistance.

226
00:19:35,320 --> 00:19:38,746
I'm giving because I see no reason why I should have more than the other.

227
00:19:39,346 --> 00:19:41,147
This is metta, loving kindness.

228
00:19:42,470 --> 00:19:52,201
All this naturally leads to undermining the negative attitudes I have in my mind, the negative feelings I have in my heart, especially if I give to someone I dislike.

229
00:19:53,178 --> 00:19:58,566
The clearer the heart and mind is of negativity, the greater is the equanimity.

230
00:19:59,607 --> 00:20:04,295
Through the practice of dana, generosity, I am developing all the perfections.

231
00:20:06,217 --> 00:20:11,365
It's important not to make heavy weather of all this, but rather to see it in the light of experimentation.

232
00:20:12,307 --> 00:20:15,550
When I decided to become a monk, I decided to give a ring away.

233
00:20:16,231 --> 00:20:18,615
It was a silver ring with a Buddhist design on it.

234
00:20:18,776 --> 00:20:19,978
I liked it very much.

235
00:20:20,583 --> 00:20:23,126
This was going to be a great act of renunciation.

236
00:20:23,928 --> 00:20:27,532
I decided I would give it away to the first person who showed any interest in it.

237
00:20:28,875 --> 00:20:37,287
As it happened, a young woman expressed a liking for it not a few days after my momentous decision, but I didn't think her worthy of it.

238
00:20:39,089 --> 00:20:45,859
Eventually, I did give it away, under those conditions, after a little self-examination and re-decision.

239
00:20:46,721 --> 00:20:49,424
I think my self-knowledge and wisdom grew a little there.

240
00:20:51,615 --> 00:20:56,201
Our growth towards the light, away from the darkness, should be a joyful exploit.

241
00:20:57,122 --> 00:20:58,804
Our targets should be manageable.

242
00:20:59,464 --> 00:21:02,167
We should not make mission impossibles.

243
00:21:03,608 --> 00:21:06,511
If we aim too high and fail, it will only disappoint us.

244
00:21:07,413 --> 00:21:10,155
Growth in mental development needs to be slow and sure.

245
00:21:10,876 --> 00:21:13,240
We need to build up our perfections in depth.

246
00:21:14,141 --> 00:21:15,182
And that takes time.

247
00:21:16,123 --> 00:21:19,767
We need to revolutionize our thinking, but without violence.

248
00:21:20,692 --> 00:21:24,076
That revolution is the movement from doing harm to doing good.

249
00:21:25,097 --> 00:21:28,542
We have to sit down every day and really examine our behaviour.

250
00:21:29,243 --> 00:21:30,925
We have to begin to do what's right.

251
00:21:32,106 --> 00:21:34,069
It's a bit like learning how to play a guitar.

252
00:21:34,671 --> 00:21:37,954
You struggle so long to twist your fingers round and get that chord.

253
00:21:38,455 --> 00:21:42,521
Then one day, there it is, a tune played with ease and delight.

254
00:21:43,863 --> 00:21:50,192
We need to see our bodies and minds as instruments we are trying to master through experimentation and practice.

255
00:21:50,594 --> 00:21:55,078
We need to develop into highly tuned, harmonious human instruments.

256
00:21:55,980 --> 00:22:00,185
This is our task, the purification and the development of mind.

257
00:22:01,247 --> 00:22:01,847
We can do it.

258
00:22:05,112 --> 00:22:07,855
Well, I hope you found this talk interesting and helpful.

259
00:22:08,996 --> 00:22:10,878
May all of you be happy and peaceful.

260
00:22:11,578 --> 00:22:14,542
May all of you attain the nirvanic peace within.

